## Finding Tickets by ID

Ticket IDs (e.g., `MILAB-5070`) are stored in the `userDefined:ID` property, NOT in page content. Notion semantic search doesn't search property values directly.

**To find a ticket by ID, search for just the numeric part within the Tasks data source:**

```
notion-search:
  query: "5070"
  data_source_url: "collection://1233a83f-f4af-814a-82dc-000b6e6d48db"
```

This works because Sprint names include the ticket ID (e.g., "Desktop 2025-12-08 ID: 5070"), which appears in search results.

**Do NOT** search for "MILAB-5070" — the prefix breaks the search. Use only the number.

## Property Schema

| Property  | Type                 | Notes                                                                 |
|-----------|----------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Title     | Text                 | `[component] Brief description` (or `[user-problem]`, `[user-request]`) |
| Team      | Relation (single)    | URL to team entry                                                     |
| Priority  | Select               | Critical / High / Medium / Low                                        |
| Category  | Select               | Bug / Task / Tech / Support (template-controlled)                     |
| Status    | Status               | Not started → Done workflow                                           |
| Sprint    | Relation (single)    | Link to sprint entry (critical tickets only)                          |
| User      | Relation (multi)     | Required for user problems/requests                                   |
| Project   | Relation (multi)     | Optional linkage to project docs                                      |
| Assignee  | People (multi)       | Notion user IDs                                                       |
| Blocked By / Is Blocking | Relation (multi) | Dependency tracking                                        |
| Estimates | Select               | Fibonacci-style values (0.1–8)                                        |

### Property Encoding Conventions

- Single-value properties stored as plain strings.
- Single relations store the canonical Notion page URL as the value.
- Multi-value relations and arrays are JSON-encoded strings, e.g. `"[\"https://www.notion.so/user\"]"`.

## Linking Practices

- Specs reference GitHub markdown using `https://github.com/milaboratory/text/blob/main/...`.
- Ticket descriptions often start with a table row: `| Links: | [Project Description](...) | [Ticket Description](...) |`.
- Specification files in the repo include a reciprocal line: `**Notion Ticket:** [ticket-name](notion-ticket-url)`.

## Figma Design References

- Tickets may embed Figma designs (shown as `external_object_instance` in Notion markdown).
- If Figma Desktop is open with the relevant file, use Figma MCP tools:
  - `get_metadata` — structure and node hierarchy
  - `get_screenshot` — visual preview of components
  - `get_variable_defs` — design tokens (colors, typography)

## Sprint Metadata

- Sprint naming format: `[Team] YYYY-MM-DD` (start date).
- Sprint states: Current, Next, Future, Last, Past.
- For critical tickets, the Sprint relation targets the entry marked **Current** in the Sprints database.
